{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Deploy host-level outbound rate limiting on UbuntuComputer using nftables/iptables (OUTPUT chain) to throttle or drop high-rate ICMP/raw protocol-1 traffic as an immediate, in-host barrier against floods.",
  "comments": "I applied iptables rules on the compromised UbuntuComputer to throttle outbound ICMP echo-request packets to the attacker 203.0.113.1. Specifically: 1) inserted a rate-limited ACCEPT rule allowing up to 10 ICMP echo-requests per second with a burst of 20 for destination 203.0.113.1; 2) inserted a DROP rule to block any additional echo-request packets to that destination. This provides an immediate, host-level control that reduces attack traffic egress even while the attacker remains active. Combined with the previously-added FortiGate egress deny and the inline Snort IDS, this creates layered defenses: host throttle -> Snort inline blocking -> FortiGate deny. Commands executed are recorded below.",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": [
    "iptables -I OUTPUT 1 -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -d 203.0.113.1 -m limit --limit 10/second --limit-burst 20 -j ACCEPT",
    "iptables -I OUTPUT 2 -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -d 203.0.113.1 -j DROP"
  ]
}

{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Deploy host-level outbound rate limiting on UbuntuComputer using nftables/iptables (OUTPUT chain) to throttle or drop high-rate ICMP/raw protocol-1 traffic as an immediate, in-host barrier against floods.",
  "comments": "Updated the host rules to address the reviewer feedback: removed the initial -m limit rule and replaced it with a stricter hashlimit rule that enforces 1 ICMP echo-request per second (burst 3) per destination IP for 203.0.113.1, then ensured a DROP fallback rule remains. This reduces the attack throughput well below the observed hping3 sending rate (~10/s) and makes the host-level control effective while the attacker remains. Actions taken:\n- Deleted the original iptables rate rule.\n- Inserted a hashlimit-based ACCEPT rule at the top of OUTPUT chain: allows 1/sec with burst 3 to destination 203.0.113.1.\n- Ensured the DROP rule is present as a fallback to block additional ICMP echo-requests.\n\nThis host-level tightening, combined with the previously added inline Snort and FortiGate egress controls, provides layered defense sufficient to stop the ongoing ICMP flood from succeeding in this environment. I recommend verifying counters with tcpdump and iptables -L -v -n to confirm drops and monitoring FortiGate/Snort logs for correlated detections.\n",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": [
    "iptables -D OUTPUT -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -d 203.0.113.1 -m limit --limit 10/second --limit-burst 20 -j ACCEPT",
    "iptables -I OUTPUT 1 -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -d 203.0.113.1 -m hashlimit --hashlimit 1/sec --hashlimit-burst 3 --hashlimit-mode dstip --hashlimit-name icmp_dst_limit -j ACCEPT",
    "iptables -R OUTPUT 2 -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -d 203.0.113.1 -j DROP"
  ]
}
